<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-581-584  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 581 584.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Microprocessor Report  June 20 1990 v4 n11 p5(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MicroDesign Resources Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Intel fights back against FPU clones. (floating pointcoprocessors) (Intel Corp.'s 80287XL coprocessor) (MostSignificant Bits) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intel Corp. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    INTC.andO;Product:   Intel 80287XL (Coprocessor) (product introduction)Intel 80287XLT (Coprocessor) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionCoprocessorsPerformance ImprovementFloating-Point ArithmeticProcessor Architecture.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Intel Fights Back Against FPU Clones In the past year, Intel has seen themarket for floating-point coprocessors attacked by two startups, IIT (SantaClara, CA) and Cyrix (Richardson, TX), with more competitors expected soon.andO;Because Intel's 287 is an old design, it has been relatively easy forcompetitors to produce chips that are pin-compatible with the 287 but muchfaster.andP;  Although some price erosion has occurred, the primary strategy IITand Cyrix have followed is to keep prices as high as possible, whilecompeting with Intel on performance.andM;Intel is now fighting back with the 287XL, a new implementation of the 287that Intel claims offers 50 percent higher performance than Intel's standard287.andP;  Intel also introduced the 287 XLT, a lower-power version in a PLCC.andO;Both chips are manufactured using Intel's CHMOS-III process.andP;  The new FPUsare based on the faster floating-point core developed for the 387 and 387SX,with a bus inteface designed for the 286.andM;Apparently, the chips are too fast for it to make sense to provide speedsorts.andP;  Instead, Intel is offering only a single version, which can operateat up at 12.5 MHz.andP;  Intel has never announced the 286 at a clock rate above12.5 MHz, but Harris and AMD have shipped 16-and 20-MHz chips.andP;  According toIntel, all systems using the faster 286 chips still run the coprocessor at 8,10, or 12.5 MHz, so the 287XL should work with 286 systems at any clock rate.andO;The &quot;suggested retail price&quot; is $370 in single units.andP;  (Compare to Motorola's68882 FPU in the previous item.)andO;</TEXT></DOC>